    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div type="letter">                <div type="text">
                    <opener>
                        <placeName><hi rend="print">Down, | Beckenham, Kent. | Railway Station | Orpington. S.E.R.</hi></placeName>
                        <salute>Dear M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. Pennington</salute>
                    </opener>
                    <div type="transcription">
                        <p>I have the pleasure to send my signature, which you wish for &amp; which you can cut off from the foot of this note<ref target="#foot.f1"/></p>
                        <p>Pray believe me | Yours sincerely | Charles Darwin  <lb/> <lb/></p>
                        <p rend="left">October 24<hi rend="superscript">th</hi>. 1878.—</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                
            </div>
            
            
            <div type="footnotes">
                <note xml:id="foot.f1">No letter from Pennington requesting CD’s autograph has been found, but she had met CD at Leith Hill Place, Surrey, on 10 August 1878 (Emma Darwin’s diary (DAR 242)). Emma mentioned the visit in a letter to <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1245.xml">William Erasmus Darwin</ref> of 11 August 1878, noting, ‘She is a nice simple mannered woman but a tremendous lion-hunter’ (DAR 219.1: 114).</note>  
            </div>    
            
